<font color="#FF0000">AN EXHIPPY RANT :)</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 26  3:41:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I grew up with the war.  It was there every night on the TV, with Walter and Dave and Chet telling us how horrible it was.  I looked at the faces of the adults in the neighborhood when they discussed who had gotten a &quot;Visit&quot;.  I watched other young people on TV march, do sit-ins and protest.  I hated the war totally and passionately as only the young and uninformed can.  Then I grew up, I read and watched.  I found a war run from a 5 sided building far away from the conflict.  A war that politics played far to great a role in.  I saw not a war where we had clear, outlined goals, but a conflict where personal agendas in Washington and Siagon changed our objectives, sometimes on a daily basis.  Even when I was young, I never blamed the soliders, but the emphereal &quot;THEY&quot;.  I read about unsung heros and engagements that killed young men on both sides.  I will make no judgement on whether the USA being in the conflict was right or wrong.  I will make judgement on Congress and the Pentagon for not making war, but piddling the lives away of thousand of men and women for little gain.  The 12 years I spent in the Air Force were always in the knowledge that I could go to war, and I could only hope that this time they would get it right.  I got out to be able to stay with my husband, but know that at anytime he could be sent into harm's way.  Hey, it's the job.  But both he and I had the choice to join.  The choice to put ourselves at risk.  Too many of the young men lost in Vietnam had no choice.  No choice of having their lives uprooted, their minds and bodies pounded until they could do the &quot;job&quot; of killing other people.  I can sympathize with, but never truely understand the things the Vietnam Vets had to go through.  I've never been there.  I've seen some pretty horrible things (I used to be an EMT), but never close to what war brings.  I have heard &quot;the war's over, forget it&quot; more times then I like to remember.  I can't forget it because it was an intergal part of my growing up, and if I who only experienced it on the periphery can't forget it, how can anyone expect those who lived it, hour by hour, day by day, forget it.  My father-in-law to the day he died had nightmares from WWII and he was only in combat once.  At this point in time, it doesn't matter if the war was right or wrong.  It is a part of too many of us.  Part and parcel with who and what we are.  Even if it's not a conscious part of our daily life, it colors our thoughts, how we react to things and our beliefs.  It needs to be recognized and accepted, that two generations of Americans have been shaped by something many people would prefer to forget.  Sorry that this has gone on so long, but it's something I've needed to vent for along time.  Everyone take care of yourselves, we lost too many, lets not lose anymore.<br>

